arXiv:2601.14102v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: A measurement of the fiducial cross section of the associated production of a Z boson and a high-$p_\mathrm{T}$ photon, where the Z decays to two neutrinos, and a search for anomalous triple gauge couplings are reported. The results are based on data collected by the CMS experiment at the LHC in proton-proton collisions at $\sqrt{s}$ = 13 TeV during 2016$-$2018, corresponding to an integrated luminosity of 138 fb$^{-1}$. The fiducial Z$\gamma$ cross section, where a photon with a $p_\mathrm{T}$ greater than 225 GeV is produced in association with a Z, and the Z decays to a $
u ar{
u}$ pair (Z($
u ar{
u}$)$\gamma$), is measured to be 23.3$^{+1.4}_{-1.3}$ fb, in agreement, within uncertainties, with the standard model prediction. The differential cross section as a function of the photon $p_\mathrm{T}$ has been measured and compared with standard model predictions computed at next-to-leading and at next-to-next-to-leading order in perturbative quantum chromodynamics. Constraints have been placed on the presence of anomalous couplings that affect the ZZ$\gamma$ and Z$\gamma\gamma$ vertex using the $p_\mathrm{T}$ spectrum of the photons. The observed 95% confidence level intervals for $CP$-conserving $h_3^{\gamma}$ and $h_4^{\gamma}$ are determined to be ($-$3.4, 3.5) $	imes$ 10$^{-4}$ and ($-$6.8, 6.8) $	imes$ 10$^{-7}$, and for $h_3^\mathrm{Z}$ and $h_4^\mathrm{Z}$ they are ($-$2.2, 2.2) $	imes$ 10$^{-4}$ and ($-$4.1, 4.2) $	imes$ 10$^{-7}$, respectively. These are the strictest limits to date on $h_3^{\gamma}$, $h_3^\mathrm{Z}$ and $h_4^\mathrm{Z}$.

arXiv:2511.15525v2 Announce Type: replace-cross Abstract: Motivated by the precise measurements of neutrino oscillation parameters at Jiangmen Underground Neutrino Observatory (JUNO), we investigate the possibility of probing the unitarity violation of lepton flavor mixing matrix solely with reactor antineutrinos. First, we stress that it is necessary to reconsider the production and detection of neutrinos in a self-consistent way, apart from neutrino propagation, when analyzing experimental sensitivities to unitarity violation. Then, concentrating on JUNO and its satellite experiment Taishan Antineutrino Observatory (TAO), we demonstrate how the event rates of inverse beta decays (i.e., $\overline{
u}^{}_e + p 	o e^+ + n$) for observing $\overline{
u}^{}_e 	o \overline{
u}^{}_e$ oscillations, and those of elastic antineutrino-electron scattering (i.e., $\overline{
u}^{}_\alpha + e^- 	o \overline{
u}^{}_\alpha + e^-$ with $\alpha = e, \mu, 	au$) for $\overline{
u}^{}_e 	o \overline{
u}^{}_\mu$ and $\overline{
u}^{}_e 	o \overline{
u}^{}_	au$ oscillations, depend on the parameters characterizing unitarity violation. Our investigation will be useful for JUNO and TAO to place independent constraints with more data in the near future.
